        output='Based on the provided financial disclosures, **yes**, the Connectivity segment revenue explicitly includes enterprise, government, aviation, and maritime revenues. \n\nHere is the detailed breakdown and description of the components that make up the Connectivity segment\'s revenue:\n\n### 1. Breakdown by Customer Segment\nThe Connectivity segment\'s revenue is primarily disaggregated into two main reporting categories: **Consumer** and **Enterprise & Government**.\n\n*   **Consumer Revenue:** \n    *   Generated primarily through monthly subscription fees for broadband services (based on geographic market and download speed) and the one-time sale of hardware.\n    *   Revenue is recognized ratably over the service period (typically month-to-month).\n    *   *Note: Consumer subscribers represented over 60% of Connectivity segment revenue in 2025.*\n*   **Enterprise & Government Revenue:**\n    *   **Enterprise (Includes Aviation & Maritime):** The text explicitly notes that enterprise revenue growth is driven by the **"aviation, maritime, and other enterprise business,"** as well as mobility. These contracts are structured as a combination of subscriptions, data consumption, and capacity.\n    *   **Government (Starshield):** Revenue generated via long-term contracts for **Starshield**, a secure satellite network designed specifically for government customers and national security applications. Revenue for certain multi-year Starshield contracts is recognized over time using a cost-to-cost input method or percentage-of-completion basis.\n    *   **Starlink Mobile (MNO Partnerships):** Revenue earned through revenue-sharing arrangements with Mobile Network Operators (MNOs) for satellite-to-mobile services (e.g., SMS, voice, light data). *A specific footnote clarifies that **Starlink Mobile service offerings are included within the Enterprise & Government revenue category**.*\n\n### 2. Breakdown by Offering (Products vs. Services)\nThe company also disaggregates total company revenue by "Products" and "Services," with the Connectivity segment capturing all product sales:\n*   **Products (Hardware):** Revenue from the sale of the **Starlink Kit** (inclusive of the user terminal). Revenue is recorded upon delivery to the customer (or upon installation for certain enterprise customers), net of sales returns and credits. *The text notes that "All of products revenue is attributable to the Connectivity segment."*\n*   **Services (Connectivity):** Revenue from broadband, mobile connectivity, and Starshield network access. This includes both fixed-price recurring subscriptions and variable-priced services based on actual data consumption.\n\n### Summary of What is Included in Connectivity Revenue:\n| Component | Description / Source of Revenue |\n| :--- | :--- |\n| **Consumer Broadband** | Monthly subscriptions and data usage for residential/consumer users. |\n| **Enterprise Broadband** | Contracts for businesses, explicitly including **aviation, maritime, and mobility** sectors. |\n| **Government / Starshield** | Long-term, secure national security and government satellite network contracts. |\n| **Starlink Mobile** | Revenue-sharing with telecom/MNO partners for direct-to-cell mobile services (categorized under Enterprise & Government). |\n| **Starlink Kits (Hardware)** | One-time sales of the satellite terminal and related equipment to all customer classes. |\n\n**In short:** If a customer is paying for internet/data access via the Starlink or Starshield constellations, or buying the physical dish to access it—whether they are a residential user, an airline (aviation), a shipping company (maritime), a telecom carrier (mobile), or a defense agency (government)—that revenue is captured within the **Connectivity Segment**.',
